T6040/J614s protected ANS register boundary, 2026-07-13
========================================================

All addresses below are the translated physical main NVMe BAR at
0x40dcc0000 plus offsets taken from drivers/nvme/host/apple.c and the J614s
AppleANS3 driver path.  The target was at a clean m1n1 EL2 proxy after a
DebugUSB reboot.  No storage commands were submitted.

1. Legacy linear-SQ control, read then same-value write

    address: 0x40dce4908 (BAR + 0x24908)
    read32:  0x00000001
    write32: 0x00000001

The read succeeded.  Rewriting the already-set value raised an SError:

    FAR:         0x40dce4908
    ESR:         0xbe000000 (SError)
    L2C_ERR_STS: 0x80
    L2C_ERR_ADR: 0x28360040dce4908
    L2C_ERR_INF: 0x1400000001

Conclusion: iBoot leaves legacy linear-SQ mode enabled, but this raw-boot
environment cannot write the firmware/SPTM-owned register.  The Linux write
is redundant and is the exact first fault in apple_nvme_reset_work().

2. Maximum-pending-command control, one read

    address: 0x40dcc1210 (BAR + 0x1210)

The read itself raised the same class of L2C access fault before a value was
returned:

    FAR:         0x40dcc1210
    ESR:         0x96000410 (data abort), followed by SError
    L2C_ERR_STS: 0x80
    L2C_ERR_ADR: 0x30160040dcc1210
    L2C_ERR_INF: 0x1400000001

No further direct register reads were attempted.  This establishes that the
T8140 static linear-SQ/NVMMU setup must be preserved rather than inspected or
rewritten from raw-boot Linux.  Dynamic queue register programming remains to
be tested through the driver with one trace checkpoint per existing access.

3. Linux preservation run

The T8140-specific driver match skipped the complete static setup block and
continued normally through ANS/RTKit readiness.  Its last two checkpoints
were:

    trace: preserving firmware-owned linear queue and NVMMU setup
    trace: before admin queue attributes write

No checkpoint after the AQA write appeared.  Therefore the normal main-BAR
write of `0x00010001` to `0x40dcc0024` is the next exact access fault.

4. Secure BAR read-only snapshot

ADT reg[9], selected by Apple's `nvme-secure-bar` property, translates to a
separate 64 KiB window at `0x44dcc0000`.  The corresponding standard NVMe
registers are readable there:

    AQA  (secure BAR + 0x24): 0x000f000f
    ASQ  (secure BAR + 0x28): 0x00000101005db000
    ACQ  (secure BAR + 0x30): 0x00000101005dc000
    CC   (secure BAR + 0x14): 0x00474000
    CSTS (secure BAR + 0x1c): 0x00000000

The queue addresses belong to firmware and cannot be reused for Linux DMA.
AppleANS2CGv2Controller::SetupAdminQueue() handles this mode through provider
platform operation `0x8027`, passing a 32-byte structure containing queue
depths plus ASQ/ACQ physical addresses, instead of writing AQA/ASQ/ACQ
directly.  The Linux path now needs the equivalent T8140 SPTM operation; no
secure-BAR write was attempted.
